      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>607 threads, <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=0>1</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=25>2</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=50>3</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=75>4</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=100>5</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=125>6</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=150>7</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=175>8</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=200>9</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=225>10</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=250>11</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=275>12</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=300>13</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=325>14</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=350>15</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=375>16</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=400>17</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=425>18</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=450>19</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=475>20</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=500>21</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=525>22</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=550>23</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=575>24</a> <a href=classes.html?class=9&start=600>25</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;<a href=classes.html?class=9&start=575>Previous Page</a>  </td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9665768659027></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9665768659027><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9665768659027>Some of ym tips, may get long =)</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9665768659027#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>149 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 1:34 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.68]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hi everyone.&nbsp;&nbsp;I play on Bristlebane and am 3 bubbs into 35, so take some of this with a grain of salt for the REALLY high level zones.  But if you are high level, why are you reading this anyway?  This will not be really well organized, I am typing as I think of it.<br>     Some group tactics:<br>     I know people have said it before, but you have enough hp and AC to stand there and take a few hits.  For example, at 35, I have 1050 hp and a 703 AC (with just my buffs) and still manage about a 162 to 168 wis.  Whatever you do, DON'T run around screaming when a mob switches to you.  It makes the tank's job a million times harder and will only get you or the group killed, and you booted out of groups.<br>     I have found that asking the tanks what buffs they want is they way to go.  It makes them happy, and generally they do not ask for everything.  This allows you to buff more often, and it makes the people you group with &gt;happy&lt;.  I still occasionally get someone who says they do not want any, so I slip one in here and there while they are busy and they do not complain.<br>     If in a group and your role is not clearly defined (another Shaman, or a Druid or two with no Cleric), talk with the others to get that role defined.  Nothing is worse than all three people hitting Gheal at the same time on someone who is down 400hp.  That is a waste of 300 mana, not a good deal.  Or everyone nuking at the same time, then a second mob jumps in and everyone is LOM *shudder*.<br>     Even when you are the healer, consider using your slow line.  This can save you multiple heals during a battle.  Until 33, I used Walking sleep.  60 mana isn't hardly anything, and for some reason it doesn't seem to get resisted often.  If you drop their speed by 30%, that is 30% of their damage you will not have to heal afterwards.  And the slow spells have a very low aggro rating.<br>     If you are 34 or higher, use that pet, but use him wisely.  When you are the main healer, he can contribute damage while you med.  But you really need to make sure you know how to use your pet.  Try playing a necro or magician for a while to get the swing of it, or be prepared to have it run off and bring some unfriendlies to you.  /pet guard here will become your best friend.  In a dungeon, ask the party if they want one.  If not, don't quible.  <br>     If you are not the primary healer, you MUST make sure the primary does not get whacked.  It takes time to taunt a mob off, and you would be suprised how fragile a Druid or Cleric is when they go for a lot of +wis gear.  ALWAYS try to save mana to catch that last heal when the Cleric calls OOM.  Your party will love you for it.<br>     Some solo tactics:<br>     Slow, slow, slow, and slow some more.  With a decent AC and Hp, but lacking defensive skills (except for dodge which gets capped at 75), you can stand there for a bit, but you will get whacked.  If they suddenly attack only at 65% frequency, well then, that allows for in combat healing and such.<br>     Try to pull with the Malise line.  I still use Malise at 35 just to drop 20 off all resistances except for disease.  60 mana for a pull spell that gives that kind of benefit is amazing.  Yeah, it won't stick all the time, but when it does, it makes life a lot easier.  Malisement squeezes my mana pool a little more than I like in a close scrap, but I use that one in groups (37 from each resist).<br>     There are three styles of soloing.  Run and nuke, stand and melee, root and dot.  All have bonuses, but run nuke is probably the worst of the bunch.  Our DD is not mana efficient.  Druids do it all the time, but they have snare and ensnare, and their DD is more mana efficient.  Makes a world of difference.<br>     Root DoT is the most time consuming to actually kill, but usually has the lowest downtime.  Simply Malise, root, DoT, add second DoT if you want, then wait for root to break.  If the root breaks after a DoT hits, just reroot and back up.  Root is a fast cast, the odds are you can get it off even on an unslowed mob.  Med until you get the root breaking or DoT has worn off messege.  Repeat.  Fairly simple, but it does take practice.  Avocets in SK can be handled this way with care at 26, although 27 is more reliable.  And if they get a resist streak, be prepared to zone.  Mana will be tight at that level, as I remember it taking 4 to 5 Envenomed breaths to knock one down.<br>     Melee is the fun one, especially if you have a pet.  It keeps defense maxed, which is Uberimportant (tm) in my opinion.  Malise,Slow,(I reversed the order of those two before I got a pet, the slow spell is more important to get other spells off) DoT, melee, nuke, cast regen, rest, repeat.  There is lots of downtime with this.  But regen helps tremendously.<br>     If you have a pet, make sure you /pet taunt to turn OFF taunt, pull with malise, send pet in to distract, slow, DoT.  At this point mob should switch to you, then melee.  I don't even nuke anymore with this method.  A quicknessed pet nipping at their heels can do a lot of damage.  Back off and heal if necessary, use root if you have to, then wade back in.<br>     One last general tip.  Regen and cannabilize can save you downtime.  Especially if you are playing a troll or Iksar.  It won't cut the downtime in half, but it will make a dent. <br><br>     Wow, that was long.  If you are on Bristlebane, give a tell to Gorthin just to say Hi or to ask about something.  I will help if I can.<br>Gorthin 35 Shaman of People's Front on Bristlebane<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
